						<summary>

						<p>On the south wall of the central shrine in the Ghṛitasthnēśvara temple.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Rājakēsarivarman (Āditya I) Year 8: 879 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>This inscription on grounds of palaeography can be assigned to the ninth century A.D. and hence the Rājakēsarivarman of this record may be identified with Āditya I.</p>						

						<p>Records that Ādittaṉ Kaṉṉaradēvaṉ, the son of the Chōḷa king <hi rend="italic">(Sōḻapperumāṉaḍigaḷ)</hi> gifted 20 <hi rend="italic">kaḻañju</hi> of gold for burning a perpetual lamp to the god Mahādēvar at Tirunettānam. The <hi rend="italic">sabhaiyār</hi> and the <hi rend="italic">ūrār</hi> of the above village received the gold and undertook to burn the lamp.</p>						

						<p>Published in <hi rend="italic">S.I.I.,</hi> Vol. V. No. 595.</p>						

						</summary>
